SIMPLE: intermission
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intermission
<hw>In`ter*mis"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>intermissio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>intermission</ets>. See
<er>Intermit</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or the state of intermitting; the state of
being neglected or disused; disuse; discontinuance.</def> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cessation for a time; an intervening period of time;
an interval; a temporary pause; <as>as, to labor without
<ex>intermission</ex>; an <ex>intermission</ex> of ten
minutes.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rest or <qex>intermission</qex> none I find.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>The short period
between acts of a play, concert, opera, or other public performance when
the audience may leave their seats for refreshment; -- it usually lasts
from 10 to 20 minutes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The temporary cessation or
subsidence of a fever; the space of time between the paroxysms of a
disease. <xex>Intermission</xex> is an entire cessation, as
distinguished from <contr>remission</contr>, or abatement of
fever.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Intervention; interposition.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Heylin.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Cessation; interruption; interval; pause; stop;
rest; suspension. See <er>Cessation</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intermissive</ent>⟦br⟧
